Description: Small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and partly a glossy surface. The rear shows a semi-circular convex surface, maybe from a leather bag. Two deep impressions of a turned cord with a width of 0.25 cm is impressed in the rear. The upper side is flat at the top and bends downwards to the sides. At the flat part an almost complete oval scarab-like seal-impression is preserved with finger impressions around it. Visible are three columnsof hieroglyphs with a cartouche in the middle, from left to right: 1) nTr nfr nb tAwi 2) (MAa.t-kA-R')| nbw (Gardiner S12) 3) jTj(?)-HD (T25). 1) the good god, the lord of the two Lands 2) Hatshepsut 3) who takes the white crown(?). The same motif can be found twice on EA86816.
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
